<h4 id="1-inspiration">1. Inspiration</h4>
<p>a circle in different coordinate systems</p>
<ol>
  <li>Cartesian Coordinate System can represents a cirlce, Polar Coordinate System can represents a circle.</li>
  <li>whatâ€™s the difference ? Itâ€™s just the same thing display in two different coordinate systems, and polar coordinate can bring calculation convience.</li>
  <li>This relationship suits the Fourier Transformation</li>
</ol>

<h4 id="2-transformation">2. Transformation</h4>

\[\hat{f}(\xi)=\int_{\infty}^{\infty} f(x) e^{-2 \pi i x \xi} d x\]

<ul>
  <li>$\hat{f}$ denotes the fourier transform of $f(x)$</li>
  <li>$\xi$ denotes frequency</li>
  <li>this whole crap is written in complex language</li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>After read this equation, you get more confused, how come $i$ comes in here?</li>
  <li>$e^{-2 \pi i \xi} = cos(-2 \pi  \xi)+ i sin(-2 \pi  \xi) $
    <ul>
      <li>the left-hand side is more concise</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h4 id="3-galois">3. Galois</h4>
<ol>
  <li>Taylor expansion just use a special family of functions which are <strong>polynomial
function</strong> to represent any transcental function.</li>
  <li>Fourier also use a special family of function which are <strong>sin and cos
function</strong> to represent any transcental function.</li>
  <li>Mathematican write formula in different language, in real number language, in
matrix language, in complex language.</li>
</ol>

